[2026-05-14 15:35:03,702 - mage.rtl_generator - INFO] RTL generator input message: [ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.SYSTEM: 'system'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nYou are an expert in RTL design. You can always write SystemVerilog code with no syntax errors and always reach correct functionality.\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nPlease write a module in SystemVerilog RTL language regarding to the given natural language specification.\nTry to understand the requirements above and give reasoning steps in natural language to achieve it.\nIn addition, try to give advice to avoid syntax error.\nAn SystemVerilog RTL module always starts with a line starting with the keyword \'module\' followed by the module name.\nIt ends with the keyword \'endmodule\'.\n\n[Hints]:\nFor implementing kmap (Karnaugh map), you need to think step by step.\nCarefully example how the kmap in input_spec specifies the order of the inputs.\nNote that x[i] in x[N:1] means x[i-1] in x[N-1:0].\nThen find the inputs corresponding to output=1, 0, and don\'t-care for each case.\n\nNote in Verilog, for a signal "logic x[M:N]" where M > N, you CANNOT reversely select bits from it like x[1:2];\nInstead, you should use concatations like {x[1], x[2]}.\n\nThe module interface should EXACTLY MATCH module_interface if given.\nOtherwise, should EXACTLY MATCH with the description in input_spec.\n(Including the module name, input/output ports names, and their types)\n\n\n\nHere are some examples of RTL SystemVerilog code:\nExample 1:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        The module should implement a XOR gate.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule(\n            input  logic in0,\n            input  logic in1,\n            output logic out\n        );\n\n            assign out = in0 ^ in1;\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\nExample 2:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        The module should implement an 8-bit registered incrementer.\n        The 8-bit input is first registered and then incremented by one on the next cycle.\n        The reset input is active high synchronous and should reset the output to zero.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule(\n            input  logic       clk,\n            input  logic       reset,\n            input  logic [7:0] in_,\n            output logic [7:0] out\n        );\n\n            // Sequential logic\n            logic [7:0] reg_out;\n            always @( posedge clk ) begin\n                if ( reset )\n                reg_out <= 0;\n                else\n                reg_out <= in_;\n            end\n\n            // Combinational logic\n            logic [7:0] temp_wire;\n            always @(*) begin\n                temp_wire = reg_out + 1;\n            end\n\n            // Structural connections\n            assign out = temp_wire;\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\nExample 3:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        The module should implement an n-bit registered incrementer where the bitwidth is specified by the parameter nbits.\n        The n-bit input is first registered and then incremented by one on the next cycle.\n        The reset input is active high synchronous and should reset the output to zero.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule #(\n            parameter nbits\n        )(\n            input  logic             clk,\n            input  logic             reset,\n            input  logic [nbits-1:0] in_,\n            output logic [nbits-1:0] out\n        );\n\n            // Sequential logic\n            logic [nbits-1:0] reg_out;\n            always @( posedge clk ) begin\n                if ( reset )\n                reg_out <= 0;\n                else\n                reg_out <= in_;\n            end\n\n            // Combinational logic\n            logic [nbits-1:0] temp_wire;\n            always @(*) begin\n                temp_wire = reg_out + 1;\n            end\n\n            // Structural connections\n            assign out = temp_wire;\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\nExample 4:\n<example>\n    <input_spec>\n        Implement the SystemVerilog module based on the following description.\n        Assume that sigals are positive clock/clk triggered unless otherwise stated.\n\n        Build a finite-state machine that takes as input a serial bit stream,\n            and outputs a one whenever the bit stream contains two consecutive one\'s.\n        The output is one on the cycle _after_ there are two consecutive one\'s.\n        The reset input is active high synchronous,\n            and should reset the finite-state machine to an appropriate initial state.\n    </input_spec>\n    <module>\n        module TopModule(\n            input  logic clk,\n            input  logic reset,\n            input  logic in_,\n            output logic out\n        );\n\n            // State enum\n            localparam STATE_A = 2\'b00;\n            localparam STATE_B = 2\'b01;\n            localparam STATE_C = 2\'b10;\n\n            // State register\n            logic [1:0] state;\n            logic [1:0] state_next;\n            always @(posedge clk) begin\n                if ( reset )\n                state <= STATE_A;\n                else\n                state <= state_next;\n            end\n\n            // Next state combinational logic\n            always @(*) begin\n                state_next = state;\n                case ( state )\n                STATE_A: state_next = ( in_ ) ? STATE_B : STATE_A;\n                STATE_B: state_next = ( in_ ) ? STATE_C : STATE_A;\n                STATE_C: state_next = ( in_ ) ? STATE_C : STATE_A;\n                endcase\n            end\n\n            // Output combinational logic\n            always @(*) begin\n                out = 1\'b0;\n                case ( state )\n                STATE_A: out = 1\'b0;\n                STATE_B: out = 1\'b0;\n                STATE_C: out = 1\'b1;\n                endcase\n            end\n\n        endmodule\n    </module>\n</example>\n\n<input_spec>\n\nI would like you to implement a module named TopModule with the following\ninterface. All input and output ports are one bit unless otherwise\nspecified.\n\n - input  clk\n - input  areset\n - input  bump_left\n - input  bump_right\n - input  ground\n - output walk_left\n - output walk_right\n - output aaah\n\nThe game Lemmings involves critters with fairly simple brains. So simple\nthat we are going to model it using a finite state machine. In the\nLemmings\' 2D world, Lemmings can be in one of two states: walking left\n(walk_left is 1) or walking right (walk_right is 1). It will switch\ndirections if it hits an obstacle. In particular, if a Lemming is bumped\non the left (by receiving a 1 on bump_left), it will walk right. If it\'s\nbumped on the right (by receiving a 1 on bump_right), it will walk left.\nIf it\'s bumped on both sides at the same time, it will still switch\ndirections.\n\nIn addition to walking left and right and changing direction when bumped,\nwhen ground=0, the Lemming will fall and say "aaah!". When the ground\nreappears (ground=1), the Lemming will resume walking in the same\ndirection as before the fall. Being bumped while falling does not affect\nthe walking direction, and being bumped in the same cycle as ground\ndisappears (but not yet falling), or when the ground reappears while\nstill falling, also does not affect the walking direction.\n\nImplement a Moore state machine that models this behaviour. areset is\npositive edge triggered asynchronous reseting the Lemming machine to walk\nleft. Assume all sequential logic is triggered on the positive edge of\nthe clock.\n\n\n</input_spec>\n')]), ChatMessage(role=<MessageRole.USER: 'user'>, additional_kwargs={}, blocks=[TextBlock(block_type='text', text='\nAnother agent has generated a testbench regarding the given input_spec:\n<testbench>\n`timescale 1 ps/1 ps\n`define OK 12\n`define INCORRECT 13\n\n// Helper module to hold the expected/golden behavior\nmodule RefModule (\n    input logic clk,\n    input logic areset,\n    input logic bump_left,\n    input logic bump_right,\n    input logic ground,\n    output logic walk_left,\n    output logic walk_right,\n    output logic aaah\n);\n    // Placeholder for the actual golden reference implementation\n    // Since the implementation is not provided, this module must behave correctly\n    // for the testbench to be valid. We assume it implements the specification.\n    // For testing purposes, we simulate a simple (though likely incorrect without the real FSM) response.\n    // In a real scenario, this would be the verified/hand-written FSM.\n    always @(posedge clk or negedge areset) begin\n        if (!areset) begin\n            walk_left <= 1\'b1; // Reset to walk left\n            walk_right <= 1\'b0;\n            aaah <= 1\'b0;\n        end else begin\n            // Placeholder logic: If ground is 0, \'aaah\' is high\n            aaah <= ~ground;\n            \n            // Simple state transition based on bumps (highly simplified)\n            if (ground == 1\'b1) begin\n                if (bump_left == 1\'b1) walk_right <= 1\'b1; else walk_right <= 1\'b0;\n                if (bump_right == 1\'b1) walk_left <= 1\'b1; else walk_left <= 1\'b0;\n                \n                // Maintain direction if no bump\n                if (bump_left == 1\'b0 && bump_right == 1\'b0) begin\n                    // This part is complex as it depends on previous state, which we don\'t track here.\n                    // For functional testing integrity, we rely on the DUT matching this reference.\n                    // Assuming initial state preference is walk_left if no instruction.\n                    if (walk_left == 1\'b1) walk_left <= 1\'b1; \n                    else if (walk_right == 1\'b1) walk_right <= 1\'b1;\n                end\n            end\n        end\n    end\nendmodule\n\n// Stimulus Generator (Kept mostly as is, focusing on necessary changes)\nmodule stimulus_gen (\n\tinput clk,\n\toutput logic areset,\n\toutput logic bump_left,\n\toutput logic bump_right,\n\toutput logic ground,\n\toutput reg[511:0] wavedrom_title,\n\toutput reg wavedrom_enable,\n\tinput tb_match\n);\n\treg reset;\n\tassign areset = reset;\n\n\ttask reset_test(input async=0);\n\t\tbit arfail, srfail, datafail;\n\t\t\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\t@(posedge clk) reset <= 0;\n\t\trepeat(3) @(posedge clk);\n\t\t\n\t\t@(negedge clk) begin datafail = !tb_match ; reset <= 1; end\n\t\t@(posedge clk) arfail = !tb_match;\n\t\t@(posedge clk) begin\n\t\t\tsrfail = !tb_match;\n\t\t\tset $display("--- Reset Test Check ---");\n\t\t\treset <= 0;\n\t\tend\n\t\tif (srfail) $display("Hint: Your reset doesn\'t seem to be working.");\n\t\telse if (arfail && (async || !datafail)) $display("Hint: Your reset should be %0s, but doesn\'t appear to be.", async ? "asynchronous" : "synchronous");\n\tendtask\n\n\t// Add two ports to module stimulus_gen:\n\t//    output [511:0] wavedrom_title\n\t//    output reg wavedrom_enable\n\n\ttask wavedrom_start(input[511:0] title = "");\n\t\tendtask\n\t\n\ttask wavedrom_stop;\n\t\t#1;\n\t\tendtask\n\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\tinitial begin\n\t\t\treset <= 1\'b1;\n\t\t\t{bump_left, bump_right, ground} <= 3\'h1;\n\t\t\treset_test(1);\n\t\t\t{bump_right, bump_left} <= 3\'h0;\n\t\t\twavedrom_start("Falling");\n\t\t\trepeat(3) @(posedge clk);\n\t\t\t{bump_right, bump_left, ground} <= 0;\n\t\t\trepeat(3) @(posedge clk);\n\t\t\t{bump_right, bump_left, ground} <= 3;\n\t\t\trepeat(2) @(posedge clk);\n\t\t\t{bump_right, bump_left, ground} <= 0;\n\t\t\trepeat(3) @(posedge clk);\n\t\t\t{bump_right, bump_left, ground} <= 1;\n\t\t\trepeat(2) @(posedge clk);\n\t\t\twavedrom_stop();\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\treset <= 1\'b1;\n\t\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\t\trepeat(400) @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\t\t\t{bump_right, bump_left} <= $random & $random;\n\t\t\t\tground <= |($random & 7);\n\t\t\t\treset <= !($random & 31);\n\t\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t\t#1 $finish;\n\t\tend\n\tendmodule\n\n\nmodule tb();\n\n\t// State tracking structure\n\ttypedef struct packed {\n\t\tint errors;\n\t\tint errortime;\n\t\tint errors_walk_left;\n\t\tint errortime_walk_left;\n\t\tint errors_walk_right;\n\t\tint errortime_walk_right;\n\t\tint errors_aaah;\n\t\tint errortime_aaah;\n\t\tint clocks;\n\t} stats;\n\t\n\tstats stats1;\n\t\n\t// --- Queue Declarations for Sequential Logic Mismatch Display ---\n\t// Inputs: clk, areset, bump_left, bump_right, ground (5 signals)\n\t// Outputs/Refs: walk_left, walk_right, aaah (3 signals)\n\t// Total signals to track per cycle: 5 (Inputs) + 3 (Outputs/Refs) + 1 (Reset status for clarity) = 9 signals tracked.\n\t// We track the 5 inputs, 3 DUT outputs, 3 REF outputs for robustness, leading to 11 signals, but we limit the queue size.\n\n\treg [1:0] input_clk_q [$];       // Clock state (for context)\n\treg input_areset_q [$];          // areset\n\treg input_bump_left_q [$];       // bump_left\n\treg input_bump_right_q [$];      // bump_right\n\treg input_ground_q [$];          // ground\n\treg [0:0] got_walk_left_q [$];    // walk_left_dut\n\treg [0:0] got_walk_right_q [$];   // walk_right_dut\n\treg [0:0] got_aaah_q [$];         // aaah_dut\n\treg [0:0] golden_walk_left_q [$]; // walk_left_ref\n\treg [0:0] golden_walk_right_q [$];// walk_right_ref\n\treg [0:0] golden_aaah_q [$];     // aaah_ref\n\treg reset_q [$];                   // Current reset state\n\n\tlocalparam MAX_QUEUE_SIZE = 10;\n\n\t// Signals for tracking the current state\n\treg current_clk = 0;\n\treg current_areset = 1\'b1;\n\treg current_bump_left = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_bump_right = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_ground = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_walk_left_dut = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_walk_right_dut = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_aaah_dut = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_walk_left_ref = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_walk_right_ref = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_aaah_ref = 1\'b0;\n\treg current_reset_state = 1\'b1;\n\n\t// --- Clock Generation ---\n\treg clk=0;\n\tinitial forever\n\t\t#5 clk = ~clk;\n\n\t// --- Signal Declarations ---\n\tlogic areset;\n\tlogic bump_left;\n\tlogic bump_right;\n\tlogic ground;\n\tlogic walk_left_ref;\n\tlogic walk_left_dut;\n\tlogic walk_right_ref;\n\tlogic walk_right_dut;\n\tlogic aaah_ref;\n\tlogic aaah_dut;\n\t\n\twire tb_match; \n\twire tb_mismatch = ~tb_match;\n\t\n\t// --- Stimulus Generation Instance ---\n\tstimulus_gen stim1 (\n\t\t.clk, clk,\n\t\t.areset, areset,\n\t\t.bump_left, bump_left,\n\t\t.bump_right, bump_right,\n\t\t.ground, ground,\n\t\t.tb_match, tb_match\n\t);\n\n\t// --- DUT and Reference Instantiations ---\n\tRefModule good1 (\n\t\t.clk, clk,\n\t\t.areset, areset,\n\t\t.bump_left, bump_left,\n\t\t.bump_right, bump_right,\n\t\t.ground, ground,\n\t\t.walk_left(walk_left_ref),\n\t\t.walk_right(walk_right_ref),\n\t\t.aaah(aaah_ref) \n\t);\n\t\n\tTopModule top_module1 (\n\t\t.clk, clk,\n\t\t.areset, areset,\n\t\t.bump_left, bump_left,\n\t\t.bump_right, bump_right,\n\t\t.ground, ground,\n\t\t.walk_left(walk_left_dut),\n\t\t.walk_right(walk_right_dut),\n\t\t.aaah(aaah_dut) \n\t);\n\n\t\n\t// --- Waveform Dumping ---\n\tinitial begin \n\t\t$dumpfile("wave.vcd");\n\t\t$dumpvars(1, tb);\n\tend\n\n\t// --- Clocking Delay Task (Maintained from original) ---\n\ttask wait_for_end_of_timestep;\n\t\trepeat(5) begin\n\t\tstrobe <= !strobe;  // This signal \'strobe\' was not defined, assuming it\'s an error in original TB and removing it, or defining it.\n\t\t// Since \'strobe\' was used but not defined, we rely solely on clock edge timing for queueing.\n\t\t@(negedge clk);\n\tendtask\n\t\n\t// Fix for undefined strobe signal in original TB: Replace wait_for_end_of_timestep with simple clock wait.\n\t\n\t// --- Mismatch Tracking Logic (Queue Implementation) ---\n\talways @(posedge clk, negedge clk) begin\n\t\tcurrent_clk <= clk;\n\t\tcurrent_areset <= areset;\n\t\tcurrent_bump_left <= bump_left;\n\t\tcurrent_bump_right <= bump_right;\n\t\tcurrent_ground <= ground;\n\t\tcurrent_walk_left_dut <= walk_left_dut;\n\t\tcurrent_walk_right_dut <= walk_right_dut;\n\t\tcurrent_aaah_dut <= aaah_dut;\n\t\tcurrent_walk_left_ref <= walk_left_ref;\n\t\tcurrent_walk_right_ref <= walk_right_ref;\n\t\tcurrent_aaah_ref <= aaah_ref;\n\t\tcurrent_reset_state <= areset;\n\n\t\t// 1. Queue Management: Enqueue data if full\n\t\tif (input_areset_q.size() >= MAX_QUEUE_SIZE - 1) begin\n\t\t\tinput_clk_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tinput_areset_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tinput_bump_left_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tinput_bump_right_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tinput_ground_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgot_walk_left_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgot_walk_right_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgot_aaah_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgolden_walk_left_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgolden_walk_right_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\tgolden_aaah_q.delete(0);\n\t\t\treset_q.delete(0);\n\t\tend\n\n\t\t// 2. Data Push\n\t\tinput_clk_q.push_back(current_clk);\n\t\tinput_areset_q.push_back(current_areset);\n\t\tinput_bump_left_q.push_back(current_bump_left);\n\t\tinput_bump_right_q.push_back(current_bump_right);\n\t\tinput_ground_q.push_back(current_ground);\n\t\tgot_walk_left_q.push_back(current_walk_left_dut);\n\t\tgot_walk_right_q.push_back(current_walk_right_dut);\n\t\tgot_aaah_q.push_back(current_aaah_dut);\n\t\tgolden_walk_left_q.push_back(current_walk_left_ref);\n\t\tgolden_walk_right_q.push_back(current_walk_right_ref);\n\t\tgolden_aaah_q.push_back(current_aaah_ref);\n\t\treset_q.push_back(current_reset_state);\n\n\t\t// 3. Check for Mismatch\n\t\tif (current_walk_left_dut !== current_walk_left_ref || \n\t\t    current_walk_right_dut !== current_walk_right_ref || \n\t\t    current_aaah_dut !== current_aaah_ref) begin\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t// Check if this is the FIRST mismatch\n\t\t\tif (stats1.errors == 0) begin\n\t\t\t\tstats1.errortime = $time;\n\t\t\t\t$display("========================================================");\n\t\t\t\t$display("!!! FIRST MISMATCH DETECTED AT TIME %0d ps !!!", $time);\n\t\t\t\t$display("Showing last %0d cycles of simulation:", input_clk_q.size());\n\t\t\t\t$display("========================================================");\n\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t// Display Queue Content\n\t\t\t\tfor (int i = 0; i < input_clk_q.size(); i++) begin\n\t\t\t\t\t// Determine if the cycle \'i\' matched or mismatched\n\t\t\t\t\tif (got_walk_left_q[i] === golden_walk_left_q[i] && \n\t\t\t\t\t    got_walk_right_q[i] === golden_walk_right_q[i] && \n\t\t\t\t\t    got_aaah_q[i] === golden_aaah_q[i]) begin\n\t\t\t\t\t\t$display("Cycle %0d: Match.", i);\n\t\t\t\t\tend else begin\n\t\t\t\t\t\t$display("Cycle %0d: MISMATCH.", i);\n\t\t\t\t\tend\n\t\t\t\t\t\n\t\t\t\t// Display signals. Use %b for 1-bit, %h for wider/group display.\n\t\t\t\t\t$display("  Time: %0d ps | Reset: %b | Clk: %b\n", $time - (input_clk_q.size()-1)*10, reset_q[i], input_clk_q[i]);\n\t\t\t\t\t$display("  Inputs: CLK=%b, ARESET=%b, B_L=%b, B_R=%b, G=%b\n", \n\t\t\t\t\t    input_clk_q[i], input_areset_q[i], input_bump_left_q[i], input_bump_right_q[i], input_ground_q[i]);\n\t\t\t\t\t$display("  Got Outputs: WL=%b, WR=%b, AAAH=%b\n", \n\t\t\t\t\t    got_walk_left_q[i], got_walk_right_q[i], got_aaah_q[i]);\n\t\t\t\t\t$display("  Expected Outputs: WL=%b, WR=%b, AAAH=%b\n", \n\t\t\t\t\t    golden_walk_left_q[i], golden_walk_right_q[i], golden_aaah_q[i]);\n\t\t\t\t);\n\t\t\t\t$display("========================================================");\n\t\t\tend\n\t\t\t\n\t\t\t// Update individual error counters (Maintaining original logic structure)\n\t\t\tif (current_walk_left_dut !== current_walk_left_ref) begin\n\t\t\t\tif (stats1.errors_walk_left == 0) stats1.errortime_walk_left = $time;\n\t\t\t\tstats1.errors_walk_left = stats1.errors_walk_left + 1\'b1;\n\t\t\tend\n\t\t\tif (current_walk_right_dut !== current_walk_right_ref) begin\n\t\t\t\tif (stats1.errors_walk_right == 0) stats1.errortime_walk_right = $time;\n\t\t\t\tstats1.errors_walk_right = stats1.errors_walk_right + 1\'b1;\n\t\t\tend\n\t\t\tif (current_aaah_dut !== current_aaah_ref) begin\n\t\t\t\tif (stats1.errors_aaah == 0) stats1.errortime_aaah = $time;\n\t\t\t\tstats1.errors_aaah = stats1.errors_aaah + 1\'b1;\n\t\t\tend\n\t\tend\n\t\t\n\t\t// Global error count update\n\t\tif (current_walk_left_dut !== current_walk_left_ref || \n\t\t    current_walk_right_dut !== current_walk_right_ref || \n\t\t    current_aaah_dut !== current_aaah_ref) begin\n\t\t\tstats1.errors = stats1.errors + 1\'b1;\n\t\tend\n\t\tstats1.clocks++;\n\tend\n\n\n\t// --- Simulation Control --- \n\tinitial begin \n\t\t// Initialization\n\t\tstats1 = \'{errors:0, errortime:0, errors_walk_left:0, errortime_walk_left:0, errors_walk_right:0, errortime_walk_right:0, errors_aaah:0, errortime_aaah:0, clocks:0};\n\t\t\n\t\t// Initial state setting for simulation start\n\t\t@(posedge clk);\n\t\t// Wait for reset sequence defined in stimulus_gen\n\t\tend\n\n\t\t// Timeout mechanism (Kept from original) \n\t\t#1000000\n\t\t$display("\\n!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!");\n\t\t$display("TIMEOUT REACHED - Forcing finish.");\n\t\t$display("!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!");\n\t\t$finish();\n\tend\n\n\t// --- Final Results Display ---\n\tfinal begin\n\t\t$display("\\n========================================================");\n\t\t$display("Simulation Summary:");\n\t\t\n\t\t// Check specific output errors\n\t\tif (stats1.errors_walk_left) $display("-> Output \'walk_left\' has %0d mismat